      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Rethinking Dams'' (editorial, July 6) says hydroelectric dams do not produce ''any of the gases that contribute to smog or global warming.''</p>
        <p>However, when vast tracts of forested land are flooded, the trees and vegetation that lie rotting in the reservoir emit methane, a greenhouse gas that is more potent than carbon dioxide.</p>
        <p>In some areas, particularly the tropics, a reservoir can emit more greenhouse gas over the lifetime of the dam than a conventional fossil-fuel power plant.</p>
        <p>With 40,000 large dams in the world and more planned, dam building and decommissioning are global issues that deserve rigorous scientific scrutiny.</p>
        <p>DEBORAH MOORE  Oakland, Calif., July 7, 1999</p>
        <p>The writer is a senior scientist at the Environmental Defense Fund.</p>
      </block>
